fields.a5: The U.S. is committed to reducing food waste by 50% by 2030. To divert food waste from landfills, OLEM promotes anaerobic digestion and composting of food waste; however, contamination of food waste with packaging (including film plastics) may complicate composting and anaerobic digestion operations and decrease the market desirability and safety of land application of the compost and digestate made from food waste. De-packaging technologies (beyond screens and filters) are increasingly being used by large food waste generators and treatment facilities as primary means of removing plastics.
fields.a6:
This product will test the performance of de-packaging equipment available on the market in real-world settings. Commonly used depackager systems in the US include DODA, BioSeparator, Doppstadt DSP 205, Dupps-Mavitec horizontal shaft-based unit with mounted flails or paddles, Gemidan Ecogi A/S, Haarslev 100-hp hammermill-based depackager, Scott Turbo Separator MEGA-THOR unit, and Tiger Depackaging System HS640 (Coker, 2019). The existing data literature review is covered under CESER QAPP, "K-LRTD-0032360-QP-1-0," entitled "Strategies for Characterization of Food Waste: Existing Data Software Tracking Tool." In addition, the CESER Quality Management Plan (QMP), "K-LRTD-0032360-QP-1-0" entitled "Strategies for Characterization of Food Waste," addresses additional information for phases one and two of this project.

The research will characterize the plastics, including quantity and particle size, in food waste streams before and after the use of de-packaging technologies. The results from this study will be useful to OLEM, restaurant and commercial kitchen operators, food retailers, composters, and wastewater treatment facility staff across the U.S. as they seek to exclude plastics (including microplastics) from the food waste stream. Key Words: Food waste, landfill diversion, waste management, sustainable materials management, plastics, food de-packaging, secondary data, existing data, EPA QA R/5, flowsa, SciFinder. This work is related to additional food waste research under SHC RA7, including life-cycle analyses of various approaches to managing food waste.

The overall project management and distribution of responsibilities among the project personnel are described in this section and shown in the figure below. The project roles and responsibilities of the various project staff and key roles for this project include the Principle Investigator (PI), Supervisor, QA Manager, and Support Personnel. This research effort falls under the Life Cycle and Decision Support Branch (LCDSB), in the Land Remediation & Technology Division (LRTD) within CESER. Other EPA and non-EPA team members may join the project team at a later date and will be covered by this QAPP.

Michael Gonzalez is the supervisor responsible for approving this QAPP. He is the Branch Chief for the Environmental Decision Analytics Branch (EDAB). He will recommend through meetings and discussions to complete all tasks so that all achievements are in accordance with this described research, review new models and their validation, and review and approve technical reports and peer review articles. He will identify staff members with the appropriate knowledge/expertise regarding the specific task being reviewed. He will review the project documents and review all briefings and presentations with assistance from team members as designated.

Wesley Ingwersen, EPA, is the project principal investigator. Dr. Ingwersen provides technical oversight to the team and plays a leading role in all modeling activities and QA. He serves as the EPA WACOR for EPA Contract EP-C-15-012 with CSRA, WA-20, which is one of two contacts and work assignments under which the supporting contractors will perform this work.
The LRTD QAM reports directly to the Deputy Division Director of LRTD. 

Currently, Jill Hoelle, serves as the QA Manager, and will provide independent QA oversight to ensure that planning and plan implementation are in accordance with the approved Quality Assurance Project Plan (QAPP). She will provide technical direction from a QA/QC perspective to EPA PIs on an as needed basis. She will enter QAPP and related products into ORD QA Track database.

David Meyer is the SHC 3.63.1 task lead. Dr. Meyer participates actively in modeling activities and documents and communicates the research.
Daniel Young is the WACOR for contract RMEERS EP-C-15-010 WA-4-41. He will assist with oversight of Software Configuration Management duties and SQA/SQC activities.

Catherine Birney assembles indicator factors and helps create food system coefficients for the model and assists in drafting associated documentation.
Kirk Scheckel is the Division Director for LRTD. He will perform reviews of model documentation and datasets.

Bill Michaud is the CSRA Work Assignment Lead for WA-20. He manages the personnel and work assignment expenses.

fields.a5:
The need to be addressed with quantitative model support is to identify and prioritize categories of goods and services (commodities) or industries that constitute the environmental hotspots within the US, a US state economy, or an average US organization’s supply chain. The model needs to produce an array of indicators of potential environmental, human health, and economic impact including direct and indirect effects associated with production and consumption of goods and services in the US. The inclusion of impacts associated with a good or service needs to be as comprehensive as possible in respect to the life cycle stages and all inputs to the economy. The model does not need to provide estimated impacts for specific goods or services (e.g. a product with a unique SKU code).

The EPA Office of Land and Emergency Management/Office of Resource Conservation and Recovery has developed the Sustainable Materials Management Tool Suite which uses the model results via the USEEIO-API. Users of these tools may include representatives of US states and regions. The EPA Office of Air and Radiation’s Center for Corporate Climate Leadership is interested in providing updated supply chain GHG emission factors. States users presenting state environmental or economic agencies or public-private partnerships would like to use state-specific versions of the model to prioritize actions within their own states. The Department of Defense may use the USEEIO framework to build components of the Defense Input-Output Model (DIO). Other federal agencies are interested in using the model for exploratory research purposes. Other users, such as those in academia, with NGOs, or with private organizations which sufficient expertise may access the USEEIO model directly to evaluate various life cycle questions of goods and services in the US.
fields.a6: The purpose of the project is to continue the development of the US Environmentally-Extended Input-Output (USEEIO) models (Yang, Ingwersen et al. 2017). These include national and state models at the highest level of detail as well as simplified or partial versions for use for analysis and comparison. This project includes continued development of the framework used to develop the model, the USEEIO Modeling Framework (https://www.github.com/USEPA/useeio/); maintenance and revision to the program used to assemble the model components and generate results, the Input-Output Model Builder or IOMB (https://github.com/USEPA/IO-Model-Builder); and the application programming interface used to make the model results available via a web service, the USEEIO API (https://github.com/USEPA/useeio_api/).
fields.a7:
The primary means of model evaluation will be though a standardized process for data quality scoring and data quality assessment. This process will be based on the LCA data quality assessment guidelines described in an EPA report (Edelen and Ingwersen, 2016) and illustrated in the USEEIO v1 documentation (Yang et al., 2017). When a USEEIO model is applied by the project team, the resulting data quality assessment scores will be used in the interpretation of the results. A secondary means of model evaluation will be through model comparison. With each build of a USEEIO model, one or more previous model versions will be selected for comparison. Results from each model will be compared using standardized comparison procedures. Reports of model comparisons will be maintained along with internal project files according to the approved Scientific Data Management plan (Ingwersen, 2015).

All new modelling techniques and methods for USEEIO models will be submitted for external peer-review. Model code and data files will be provided to reviewers, so they will have the means of checking model output against reported model results as well as reviewing the scientific validity of the described methods.

fields.a5: Since the Deepwater Horizon Oil Spill in 2010, interest in products and procedures to clean up an oil spill has become a high priority. Unintentional releases of oil into coastal waters may result in oil becoming stranded on shorelines and salt water marshes. Stranded oil can have a severe effect on the local environment, including toxic exposures and smothering of biota in direct contact with the oil. An oil spill can be contained and remediated via mechanical containment using booms, recovery using skimmers and destruction by in-situ burning. Various products have been developed to augment these physical means. The QAPP entitled “Development and Revision of Procedures for the Code of Federal Regulations (CFR) Appendix C to Part 300, Oil Spill Product Testing Protocols”, EPA QA Track ID L14866-QP-1-6, covers the procedures for evaluating the effectiveness of chemical dispersants that break up and dissipate oil from the surface into the water column and for biological additives that encourage bioremediation by hydrocarbon degrading bacteria.
fields.a6: The primary objective of this project is to develop a laboratory testing protocol using various oil attachment matrices (sand, glass, resins, filters, etc) and simulated seawater for determining the effectiveness of SWA products. To accomplish this objective, the focus will be on determining the reproducibility of the draft testing protocol for evaluating SWA effectiveness in seawater through replicate and independent test runs. Once there is an established protocol using seawater, effectiveness of SWA products will be evaluated using artificial freshwater to determine applicability of the protocol in cleaning up inland spills, as a secondary objective.  Additionally, the BFT will be used to differentiate the SWA products as either “lift and float” or “lift and disperse” based on their mechanism of action. Current understanding is that only products that are “lift and float” will be considered for possible listing on the NCPPS as an SWA.
fields.a7: This is an EPA Category A research project. In order to address the project objectives, generation of reliable data is vital. The use of calibrated measuring and weight equipment, appropriate laboratory ware, unadulterated chemicals from the same vendor as well as maintaining quality control measures during sample analysis strengthens the generation of reliable data. The QA Quality Control (QC) and verification criteria for the analytical methods used during this project are discussed in Section B.

This includes yearly refresher training as required by Safety, Health, and Environmental Management (SHEM). The Health and Safety Plan (HASP) on file includes information on the project-specific safety training and requirements.

fields.a5:
EPA’s Office of Resource Conservation and Recovery (ORCR), in an effort to ensure responsible national management of hazardous and nonhazardous waste and provide technical assistance to all levels of government to establish safe waste management practices, develops information about Sustainable Materials Management (SMM).  SMM is a systemic approach to using and reusing materials more productively over their entire life cycles.  By looking at a product's life cycle, one can find new opportunities to reduce environmental impacts, conserve resources, and reduce costs. In order to understand where opportunities for improvement exist, one must measure a product’s production, use, and entrance into the waste management stream.  To accomplish these objectives, ORCR creates and/or supports research on the U.S. Environmental Extended Input-Output tools and National municipal solid waste Facts and Figures documents.  The Office of Research and Development (ORD) puts effort towards accomplishing these desires.  ORD’s efforts in secondary data collection and process and system modeling for municipal solid waste management pathways, used in the above tools and documents, are the subject of this QAPP.  The research described in this QAPP includes approaches being developed by CESER researcher through the Sustainable and Healthy Communities (SHC) National Research Program.  

The researchers will collaborate with the Office of Resource Conservation and Recovery (ORCR) to revise existing data or add new data to capture waste management within the U.S. as accurately as possible.  The researchers will also evaluate data availability and reliability to determine if mismanagement pathways, such as escaped trash or litter, can be included in future Facts and Figures reports.  The effort will address three focus areas.  For focus area (1), the research will evaluate the current Facts and Figures report and methodology and provide data and analysis to improve transparency and communication of results to stakeholders.  As part of this effort, the researchers will explore opportunities to replace proprietary data currently used to generate the Facts and Figures data with data from the public domain.  The current methodology used to calculate recycling rates will be compared with alternative approaches for the purpose of capturing emerging concerns related to the efficiency and challenges of material recycling facilities in sustainable materials management.  For focus area (2), the researchers will develop or improve management pathway models for the Facts and Figures using data describing current waste management activities across the U.S.  Finally, focus area (3) will develop data and models describing industrial waste generation and management because this category of waste is of growing importance to ORCR's waste measurement program. The combination of activities will generate data and methods with detailed documentation that can be shared with partners and stakeholders, including state and local solid waste managers.  The outcomes of this work will inform the development of the U.S. Environmentally Extended Input Output (USEEIO) model and the SMM Prioritization Tool.  Municipal solid waste management in the U.S. is complex and varies greatly from state to state.  Sufficiently capturing this variability in the proposed research will be the greatest challenge because it will require managing the trade-off between maximizing the level of detail in the models and data and minimizing the time required to address the immediate interests.
fields.a6:
This project has two major divisions of municipal solid waste (MSW) treatment pathways: plastics and anaerobic digestion.  The plastics portion of the work provides existing data and models describing the generation and management of plastic waste, with an emphasis on recycling processes and secondary markets.  The management of plastics has been identified as a key need in Sustainable Materials Management (SMM).  Each year the Office of Resource Conservation and Recovery (ORCR) develops a snapshot of municipal solid waste characterization in the U.S. to advance SMM and publishes these estimates in the annual Facts and Figures report.  The report provides statistics for waste management pathways and currently includes generation, recycling, energy recovery, and landfilling.  While the Facts and Figures report includes plastics, there are numerous data gaps surrounding the generation and management of plastics within the economy.  This product adds more resolution to the national material balance of plastics by improving estimates for the source and tonnage of plastic waste generation, including modeling the release of plastic materials to the environment.  Management pathway models for plastics will be enhanced by tracking plastics flows to landfill, conversion technologies, and specific recycling markets while trying to include first estimates of unmanaged material losses to close material balances.  Process models for the management of plastic wastes will be developed to integrate the knowledge contained in this product with waste input-output research (i.e., manifested as the U.S. Environmentally Extended Input Output (USEEIO) model and ORCR’s SMM Prioritization Tool).  Thus, the final products from this work will enhance the information that can be provided in both the Facts and Figures report and the USEEIO model underlying the SMM Prioritization Tool.

The second major division of the project is anaerobic digestion.  This research involves the development of secondary data and process models describing the use of anaerobic digestion for the treatment of organic municipal solid waste.  As described above, the current version of the Facts and Figures report provides information on waste management pathways for generation, recycling, energy recovery, and landfilling.  Energy recovery is a broad pathway and can include many technologies.  Anaerobic digestion is an emerging energy recovery technology of interest to the ORCR because of the challenges of managing the large volumes of organic waste generated in the United States, including food waste.  This research combines the knowledge from existing efforts in the Agency to better understand anaerobic digestion with current operational data for facilities in the continental United States to develop material flow models for anaerobic digestion that are consistent with the Facts and Figures methodology.  As part of this effort, process models will be developed for anaerobic digestion that can be implemented in the waste input-output framework being developed for the USEEIO model to track materials throughout the economy, which is also the basis for ORCR’s SMM Prioritization Tool.  

The steps within each major division of this research are iterative processes that address the overall system flows and the process models.  For instance, as flows of feed material (plastic or food waste, for example) are updated for overall system flows, the feed material flows for individual processes can be updated.  More interesting results might include a range of feed material flows, thus leading to processes with different production rates.  As processes are modeled, the effluent results will determine total amounts and distribution of amounts sent for further processing.  These results can affect the flows in the overall systems, especially where recycling creates loops of material use.  As the project timeline below shows, at some point the iteration between models will have to stop to report results.  Just as Facts and Figures presents statistics as a snapshot in time, the models developed in this research will provide insight at a particular time.  The intent is for the models to be easily updated to provide new results when new information is available in the future.
fields.a7:
The Project Team will use a variety of quality control (QC) techniques to ensure data quality and to identify potential sources of error during this work.  The QC methodologies are discussed conceptually below.

A.7.1	Data Acquisition and Management

Consistent with EPA’s QA requirements, this QAPP will ensure the selection of appropriate values for technical analyses to be conducted.  Specific elements addressed by this QAPP include:
	identifying the sources of existing data,
	presenting the hierarchy for data selection,
	describing the review process and data quality criteria/metrics,
	discussing quality checks and procedures should errors be identified, and
	explaining how data will be managed, analyzed, and interpreted.

Data and information will be found initially from internet searches and reading trade journals to identify sources believed to be credible and/or reputable.  The data and information used to populate the database and develop material flow system and process models may come from reports, technical publications, webpages, and discussions with experts on the subject matter.  Specifically, sources to be examined include (but are not necessarily limited to): 
•	Scientific or engineering publications, including peer-reviewed journal articles
•	Local, state, or federal regulatory agency rules, laws, or guidance, in the form of reports, documents, or website information
•	Scientific or industry trade organizations (resource-recycling.com, recyclingtoday.com, biocycle.net) or related research organizations

As data sources and information are gathered, the project team will examine each source to assess whether the information and data are appropriate and support the research and analytical efforts to meet the research objectives.  
Databases and spreadsheets will be used to store and relate data collected as applicable.  The design of the databases / spreadsheets will be appropriate for the intended use for the required analytical tasks.  For the database, the structure is expected to consist of rows of materials (e.g., polyethylene terephthalate, high density polyethylene, food waste) and column of flows (e.g., overall U.S. production, overall U.S. use, international trade amount, discarded amount, recycled amount) with more specific sub-headings as needed (e.g., mechanical recycling amount, chemical recycling amount).  For process models, data on product yields, byproducts, separation equipment, etc. will be collected into a spreadsheet for use in modeling.  Data entered into the database will be referenced to the source of the data where available.  Other data attributes (i.e., metadata, for example, product type, physical and chemical properties) will be incorporated into the database as available.  Database / spreadsheet design specifications will be peer-reviewed to ensure they meet the criteria set forth to meet the purpose of the specific analytical task.  Tables and fields will be unambiguously named.  Output tables and reports will be checked for accuracy by the Project Lead to ensure they meet project requirements and the requirements for EPA.

fields.b1_1: Microplastics are plastic particles less than 5 mm in one dimension that pollute the environment such as rivers, lakes, and oceans. The plastics are organic chemicals that are composed of polymers that contain various carbon base units (e.g., ethylene, propylene, styrene), functional groups and sizes. Microplastics are classified into two segments, primary and secondary types. Primary microplastics include fragmented fibers and particles generated in the washing drainage of food waste of the particle materials. Secondary microplastic is formed in the process of being gradually broken down into small fragments by the force of waves, wind, and ultraviolet rays from the sun over a longer period of time.  Microplastics can be analyzed using bulk analytical techniques such as elemental analysis, pyrolysis gas chromatography/mass spectrometry (GC/MS) or total organic carbon (TOC), or they can be analyzed at the microscopic level using stereomicroscopy such as digital microscopes, scanning electron microscope (SEM) or transmission electron microscope (TEM), or using Raman and infrared microscopy. While microscopes are typically used for initial characterization or for a qualitative assessment of microplastics in the environment, quantitative analysis of microplastics is currently mainly performed using Fourier transformation infrared spectroscopy/microscopy (FTIR/μFTIR).
fields.b1_2: The focus of this research is plastic waste generated from food packaging, which typically winds up as road litter or it is found in wastebaskets, streams, rivers, wastewater treatment plants (typically in biosolids) or in landfills. In this study, initially, a survey of of domestic locations, and various other restaurants and commercial businesses serving food (e.g., caterers) will be conducted to determine the type of depackaging equipment being used in the facility and the type of waste being generated. Commonly used depackager systems in the US include DODA, BioSeparator, Doppstadt DSP 205, Dupps-Mavitec horizontal shaft-based unit with mounted flails or paddles, Gemidan Ecogi A/S, Haarslev 100-hp hammermill-based depackager, Scott Turbo Separator MEGA-THOR unit, and Tiger Depackaging System HS640 (Coker, 2019). Based on the survey results, 2-3 facilities that encompass each different type of wastes and depackaging equipment being used will be selected for sample collection. Food waste from houses, restaurants, and groceries will be collected in Ziploc bags and transported back to EPA's AWBERC Facility for analysis. At each location, approximately 100g of material is expected to be collected. Ziploc bags containing Ottawa sand or similar material will be used as a control and trip blank. The samples will be stored in a freezer at -20C until they are processed for analysis.
fields.b1_3: Initially, a survey of of domestic locations, and various other restaurants and commercial businesses serving food (e.g., caterers) will be conducted to determine the type of depackaging equipment being used in the facility and the type of waste being generated. Based on the survey results, 2-3 facilities that encompass each different type of wastes and depackaging equipment being used will be selected for sample collection. A sampling of food waste at each location will be conducted after written approval by the appropriate owner/manager. Approximately 100g of material will be collected in Ziploc bags at each domestic or commercial location.
fields.b2_1: Once the sampling locations are identified and appropriate permissions are obtained, from the owners, a section of the sampling container (waste bins or dumpsters) will be randomly chosen and the contents of the section mixed with a stirring rod. From this section, approximately 100g of material will be collected into Ziploc bags and transported to AWBERC for storage until they are ready for analysis.
fields.b2_2: Ottawa sand that has been muffled in an oven at 600C will be used as a control for this study. For a trip blank, 100g of the muffled sand will be placed in a Ziploc bag and transported to the sampling sites and back to AWBERC. These samples will be processed using the same procedure as for the field samples. In addition, a fresh batch of muffled sand will be used as a laboratory control at the time of sample processing and analysis.
fields.b2_3: Spatulas or tongs will be used to collect samples from waste bins or dumpsters. These will be washed with SuperQ water that will be brought to the field and wiped with antimicrobial wipes before use at the next sampling location. The outsides of the Ziploc bags will be sprayed with 70% ethanol prior to placing them in coolers for transport back to AWBERC.
fields.b2_4: Ziploc bags are expected to be used to collect all samples in the field. Approximately 100g of waste material will be collected at each sampling location. A Ziploc bag filled with Ottawa sand muffled at 600C will be used as a trip blank on field sampling days.
fields.b2_5: Samples will be labelled using the name of the concern, sampling location and a date. For example, Kroger-Everton-05252020 will imply that the samples was collected at a Kroger grocery store in Everton on May 25, 2020.
fields.b2_6: Samples from the field will be stored in a freezer at -20C until they are ready to be processed. Since microplastics are not known to degrade in the environment, there is no hold time for sample processing.
fields.b2_7: Samples will be collected in Ziploc bags, disinfected and stored in a cooler for transportation back to the EPA. Each Ziploc bag containing the sample will be labelled at the time of collection using a sharpie, and a chain of custody will be updated with the new sample at the place of collection. Upon transport back to AWBERC, the samples will be transferred to a -20C freezer and the chain of custody signed by the sample custodian.
fields.b3_1: No field analysis is anticipated for samples collected from the field in this study.
fields.b3_2: Prior to analyzing the waste material collected in Ziploc bags, the samples will be dried in an oven at 105C to remove moisture, and once dry, the samples will be sieved through a sieve shaker to obtain a material with different sizes. Samples contained in each mesh will initially be qualitatively analyzed using a microscope to determine the presence of plastics. Once identified, these plastic particles will be isolated and quantitatively analyzed using SOP K-LRTD-SOP-1203-0 entitled Fourier Transformation Infrared (FTIR) Spectroscopic Analysis. Identification by Spectral Libraries. Shimadzu “LabSolutions” software for FTIR includes approximately 12,000 spectra in a proprietary spectral library. Furthermore, a "Thermally degraded plastic library" is available as an optional software package, which contains a total of 111 spectra of unheated and heat-degraded at 200°C to 400°C for 13 types of plastics. Chemical degradation of plastics is almost always considered as oxidative degradation.
fields.b3_3: The calibration procedures described in the SOP K-LRTD-SOP-1203-0 entitled Fourier Transformation Infrared (FTIR) Spectroscopic Analysis will be followed under this QAPP.
fields.b4_1: A 4-point calibration will be performed using a known standard at the beginning of the analysis. The coefficient of regression should be > 0.99. The calibration should be run again if these criteria are not met. All samples and controls will be measured in triplicate using the FTIR. The RSD should be < 10%. Occasional data outside the acceptance limits will be flagged. If more than 30% of the samples fail these criteria, the problem will be investigated and the analysis repeated. The spectra from each sample should have a match quality > 500. If these criteria are not met, the problem should be investigated and the sample reanalyzed.

fields.b1_1: The selection of the level of the detail of the models used will depend upon the user (program office, region, state, organization, etc.) or the research need and data availability to support the creation of the different models. Applications of the model are at the discretion of the other end users, except when used for demonstrative purposes by the project team. The goal of the USEEIO model is to use the most recent environmental data available along with the most recent economic data with which they can be paired. There must be a direct correspondence between both the vintage and scope of the environmental and economic data to pair them. As a matter of convention, when the underlying input-output data are of a different year than the environmental data, gross output data are collected for the year of the environmental data to develop coefficient with matching numerator and denominator dollar year, and the current price assumption (Miller and Blair, 2009) is used to assume the direct requirements derived from the input-output data are applicable to the dollar year of the model.
fields.b1_2: The general type of model used is an environmentally-extended input-output model (EEIO). This is an established model form used for life cycle assessment, environmental footprinting, national and regional environmental analysis, among other purposes. These models combine economic data in input-output tables describing transactions between industries and their associated commodities with environmental data on chemical releases and resources used by industry. The industry coverage includes agricultural, manufacturing, mining, utilities, transport, service and government activities in the US; virtually the entire US economy aggregated into sectors, with a level of resolution of ~400 sectors for the most detailed model. The environmental coverage includes emissions to air, water, soil, resources consumed, and wastes generated. The regional coverage varies depending on the model; the USEEIOv1 model is a single region model representing the average US region; state models are planned to be two-region models representing the state of interest and the rest of the US. The temporal coverage is annual for a single year and has a single time-step.
fields.b1_3: The primary models to be created in support of the EPA Sustainable Materials Management program, include national and state-level good and services-based models with a high or medium level of good and service detail (~ 400 goods and services for high or ~120 goods and services for medium), and ~ 2000 environmental or social-economic flows. These models are called the USEEIO models here. Other models of the same type (EEIO model) developed for analytical or testing purposes will be called supporting models.
fields.b2_1: The model uses economic input-output tables and gross output data from the Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA). The most recent detailed input-output data are used for the ‘A’ matrix of the model although more aggregate input-output data may be used for testing/model evaluation. The ‘Make’ and ‘Use’ tables are the primary input-output tables that are combined to form the A matrix; the gross output data and associated price indices are used for the denominator to develop coefficients in the form of a physical unit per dollar output data in the ‘B’ satellite tables. The input-output tables, gross output and price index data are publicly available through the BEA Interactive Data and API data outlets (BEA, 2018a; BEA 2018b). For state models, the input-output table data must be split into regions for the state and the rest of the US. This research will investigate two options for the economic components of state models: (1) creating an original state economic model, or (2) using an existing state economic model. For option 1, a methodology will be developed. The methodology will integrate existing national input-output tables with sources to estimate state industry output, trade models between states, and data determining the nature of sectors as locally-consumed or traded. Trade estimates will use various approaches, including the use of commodity flow data from the Freight Analysis Framework model (https://faf.ornl.gov/fafweb/Default.aspx), data on whether or not commodities are consumed locally or are traded (http://www.clustermapping.us/), and estimates of regional gross commodity output. Gross output estimates for states and regions will come from a variety of sources, including the US Census Bureau and the Bureau of Labor Statistics. For these models, input-output tables will be checked for balance. Established input-output table balancing procedures, such as RAS, will be used to rebalance matrices when balances are not met. For option (2), the suitability of a state economic input-output model from the Wisconsin Nati
fields.b2_4: Total US commodity and industry output data will be used for rebalancing. These are primarily derived from the BEA input-output tables. For state models, the sum of total commodity and total industry output for the state and rest of the US as derived from the row and column sums of the model Use table must match the total published US commodity and industry output within a level of tolerance. The level of tolerance will be based on model application.
fields.b3_3:
The model uses environmental data from various sources of government agencies, including EPA, USDA, USGS, EIA. The EPA data, including the Toxic Release Inventory, National Emissions Inventory, Greenhouse Gas Reporting Program, RCRA Biennial Report, and Discharge Monitoring Report, will come from the Standardized Emissions and Waste Inventory (StEWI) program, which is maintained in a separate project (QA ID: G-LRTD-0031522 ‘Life Cycle Assessment Data Management’). Data from other agencies are acquired via web services or as static files. To incorporate these data into ‘B’ matrices, data are grouped in the BEA’s NAICS-derived sector classification, adjusted to a standardized metric unit, any data redundancies are removed, and each resulting value will be an exchange or stressor, consisting of the value, the information about the resource/emission, and the product class it is associated with. The satellite tables have values of physical units -- of resource use, waste generated, or release to the environment – per USD gross output of the given product class. Each exchange will be mapped onto a flow in the Federal LCA Commons standardized elementary flow list, which is maintained in a separate project (G-LRTD-0031522 ‘Life Cycle Assessment Data Management’), using mapping files provided in that project. 

A municipal solid waste (MSW) satellite table is included in the model in addition to hazardous waste information obtained from the RCRA biennial report. MSW generation can occur in both commercial and residential locations. The MSW satellite table initially models commercial waste generation by the industrial sector. The waste generation data is taken from a 2014 waste characterization study performed by the state of California (CalRecycle, 2015). The data from the report is used to develop ton-per-employee-per-year (TPEPY) generation rates. Commercial MSW generation for the national or state models can be calculated using employment data obtained from the Quarterly Census of Employment and Wages (QCEW) maintained by the Bureau of Labor Statistics (https://www.bls.gov/cew/). Residential MSW generation will be modeled using data reported in waste characterization studies made available through appropriate state agencies that oversee solid waste management.

For the ‘C’ matrix, these data consistent of impact factors derived from TRACI 2.1, which was developed in another EPA project, other published impact methods, or simply group different flows by type (e.g., identifying different hazardous waste flows as a group called ‘hazardous waste’). If available, impact factors developed that are compatible with the Federal LCA Commons elementary flow list will be used.

fields.b1_1: Support for FLOWSA development. EPA has initiated work on a model called FLOWSA (Flow Sector Attribution) to retrieve, parse and store data on flows of resources and chemicals and attribute these to industry sectors. The FLOWSA model is part of the EPA’s broader USEEIO work under the Sustainable and Healthy Communities project 7, Output 1. All programming code is stored in EPA GitHub space at https://github.com/USEPA/flowsa. The contractor shall assist the EPA research team in writing and testing Python scripts to retrieve, parse, transform and store data for FLOWSA at the direction of the EPA WACOR. EPA will provide the contractor with a conceptual plan for FLOWSA, technical and functional requirements as a background for how FLOWSA should function. EPA will provide direction in regular meeting platforms and use a cloud instance of Jira for issue management in the form of a scrum board and assign issues to the contractor. The contractor shall regularly provide issue updates using this platform. This work should be completed under the G-STD-0030017-QP-1-4 QAPP.
fields.b1_2: EPA develops new and updated USEEIO models along with updates to the USEEIO API code and documentation. The contractor shall deploy the USEEIO API software, new or updated models, and API documentation to the API staging and production servers at the request of the EPA COR. fields.b3_5:
The model uses economic input-output tables and gross output data from the Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA). The most recent detailed input-output data are used for the ‘A’ matrix of the model although more aggregate input-output data may be used for testing/model evaluation. The ‘Make’ and ‘Use’ tables are the primary input-output tables that are combined to form the A matrix; the gross output data and associated price indices are used for the denominator to develop coefficients in the form of a physical unit per dollar output data in the ‘B’ satellite tables. The input-output tables, gross output and price index data are publicly available through the BEA Interactive Data and API data outlets (BEA, 2018a; BEA 2018b).

For state models, the input-output table data must be split into regions for the state and the rest of the US. This research will investigate two options for the economic components of state models: (1) creating an original state economic model, or (2) using an existing state economic model. For option 1, a methodology will be developed. The methodology will integrate existing national input-output tables with sources to estimate state industry output, trade models between states, and data determining the nature of sectors as locally-consumed or traded. Trade estimates will use various approaches, including the use of commodity flow data from the Freight Analysis Framework model (https://faf.ornl.gov/fafweb/Default.aspx), data on whether or not commodities are consumed locally or are traded (http://www.clustermapping.us/), and estimates of regional gross commodity output. Gross output estimates for states and regions will come from a variety of sources, including the US Census Bureau and the Bureau of Labor Statistics. For these models, input-output tables will be checked for balance. Established input-output table balancing procedures, such as RAS, will be used to rebalance matrices when balances are not met. For option (2), the suitability of a state economic input-output model from the Wisconsin National Data Consortium (Rutherford and Schreiber, 2018) will be assessed. Suitability will be determined based on methodology and data sources used, vintage of data used, formats of available models and compatibility with needs. The selection of either option (1) or (2), or both, will be based on needs, timing, and level of effort.

Methods to further disaggregate the commodity classifications for BEA and hybridize the model with mass-based data for the A matrix will be developed in this project to provide finer resolution to goods and services in the model. In these cases, the model ‘A’ matrix will grow to include new sectors beyond those present in the BEA Make and Use tables.
fields.b3_7: Traditional model calibration does not apply to environmentally-extended input-output models, with the exception of input-output matrix balancing procedures that may be used to balance the input-output tables in models for which these tables are not provided but must be derived.

fields.b1_1: The goal of the USEEIO model is to use the most recent environmental data available along with the most recent economic data with which they can be paired. There must be a direct correspondence between both the vintage and scope of the environmental and economic data to pair them. As a matter of convention, when the underlying input-output data are of a different year than the environmental data, gross output data are collected for the year of the environmental data to develop coefficient with matching numerator and denominator dollar year, and the current price assumption (Miller and Blair, 2009) is used to assume the direct requirements derived from the input-output data are applicable to the dollar year of the model.
fields.b1_2:
The model uses environmental data from various sources government agency, including EPA, USDA, USGS, EIA. The EPA data, including the Toxic Release Inventory, National Emissions Inventory, Greenhouse Gas Reporting Program, RCRA Biennial Report, and Discharge Monitoring Report, will come from the Standardized Emissions and Waste Inventory (StEWI) program, which is maintained in a separate project (QA ID: G-LRTD-0031522 ‘Life Cycle Assessment Data Management’). Data from other agencies are acquired via web services or as static files. To incorporate these data into ‘B’ matrices, data are grouped in the BEA’s NAICS-derived sector classification, adjusted to a standardized metric unit, any data redundancies are removed, and each resulting value, will be an exchange or stressor, consisting of the value, the information about the resource/emission, and the product class it is associated with. The satellite tables have values of physical units -- of resource use, waste generated, or release to the environment – per USD gross output of the given product class. Each exchange will be mapped onto a flow in the Federal LCA Commons standardized elementary flow list, which is maintained in a separate project (G-LRTD-0031522 ‘Life Cycle Assessment Data Management’), using mapping files provided in that project. 

A municipal solid waste (MSW) satellite table is included in the model in addition to hazardous waste information obtained from the RCRA biennial report. MSW generation can occur in both commercial and residential locations. The MSW satellite table initially models commercial waste generation by industrial sector. The waste generation data is taken from a 2014 waste characterization study performed by the state of California (CalRecycle, 2015). The data from the report is used to develop ton-per-employee-per-year (TPEPY) generation rates. Commercial MSW generation for the national or state models can be calculated using employment data obtained from the Quarterly Census of Employment and Wages (QCEW) maintained by the Bureau of Labor Statistics (https://www.bls.gov/cew/). Residential MSW generation will be modeled using data reported in waste characterization studies made available through appropriate state agencies that oversee solid waste management.

For the ‘C’ matrix, these data consistent of impact factors derived from TRACI 2.1, which was developed in another EPA project, other published impact methods, or simply group different flows by type (e.g., identifying different hazardous waste flows as a group called ‘hazardous waste’). If available, impact factors developed that are compatible with the Federal LCA Commons elementary flow list will be used.

fields.b2_3: The general type of model used is an environmentally-extended input-output model (EEIO). This is an established model form used for life cycle assessment, environmental footprinting, national and regional environmental analysis, among other purposes. These models combine economic data in input-output tables describing transactions between industries and their associated commodities with environmental data on chemicals releases and resources used by industry. The industry coverage includes agricultural, manufacturing, mining, utilities, transport, service and government activities in the US; virtually the entire US economy aggregated into sectors, with a level of resolution of ~400 sectors for the most detailed model. The environmental coverage includes emissions to air, water, soil, resources consumed, and wastes generated. The regional coverage varies depending on the model; the USEEIOv1 model is a single region model representing the average US region; state models are planned to be two region models representing the state of interest and the rest of the US. The temporal coverage is annual for a single year and has a single time-step

Model verification will be completed using a number of techniques. Model generated total environmental emissions associated with full US output will be checked against national emission or resource use totals. Model generated total commodity output to meet US output demand will be checked against reported US total commodity output.
Because methods for quantitative model uncertainty analysis for EEIO models have not been established, model uncertainty is primarily addressed using sensitivity analysis, gravity analysis, and model comparison methods. The implementation of these types of analysis performed will vary based on the possible model uses. See Section 8.1.
National emissions or resource use totals will come from the original data providers used to create the sources (see Section 4.3 and Figure 2). Total US commodity output will be derived from the published Use table.
Model validation tests (see Section 5.2) will include import of independent data (section 7.3) and comparison of these data against model generated totals.

fields.b1_1: The main objective of the proposed research is to evaluate, by laboratory testing, the efficiency of SWA products to remove weathered oil from a surface. The first step in this proposed research will be to use the BFT (see Appendix B) to differentiate the SWA products for oil removal as either “lift and float” or “lift and disperse”. While laboratory testing will continue with all SWA products, only products that are “lift and float” will probably be considered for listing on the NCPPS. As a clean-up procedure in the environment, oil floating on an aqueous surface is easier to contain than oil that has been dispersed into the water column.
fields.b1_2: Most of the details of the sampling methods can be found in Appendices A and B. IFO-120 crude oil has been procured by the WACOR from the Office of Land and Emergency Management and Bureau of Safety and Environmental Enforcement. These oils are stored at room temperature in AWBERC Rm 703. All manufacturers of SWA products on the NCPPS were contacted and a one liter sample of their product was requested. Only about half of the current 56 SWA products on the NCPPS have been received after three request attempts. Those SWA products that have been obtained from the manufacturers are stored at room temperature in AWBERC Rm 703. All products are being stored under the same conditions in the laboratory according to the manufacturer’s recommendations. Shelf life for the different SWA products varies (18 months to unlimited) and should be considered when the testing begins.
fields.b1_3: To summarize the proposed SWA research, oil is applied to the testing matrix surface, allowed to weather for some time followed by addition of the SWA product to the oil. The oiled matrix is then mixed with SWA product to release oil and any oil remaining on the surface is extracted into a known volume of DCM. All DCM extracts of each replicate will be quantified to determine the mass of oil in extracts. The aqueous solution (artificial freshwater or ocean saltwater) will also be extracted during preliminary research to determine the mass balance of the system. The efficiency of the SWA will be determined based on the mass of oil released from the testing matrix surface to the total mass of the oil applied. For each SWA product tested, six replicates will be analyzed. The decision of six replicates was based on the development of effectiveness tests for dispersants, where six replicates were required so that one outlier could be removed leaving five replicates remaining to statistically strengthen the test. This has been previously published by the US EPA (Sorial et al., 2004).
fields.b2_1: Crude Oil: Preliminary testing will use IFO-120 or PBC oil, with other possible crude oils to be decided upon later. The choice of other oils will be considered once preliminary testing has finalized using IFO-120 crude oil and selected substrate matrix. The volume of oil to be used WA 4-05 QAPP for Development and Testing of a SWA Product Efficiency Protocol Date: January 7, 2020 Revision Number: 7 Page 19 of 38 will vary from 50 to 500 µl, applied as one large drop or as several small drops on the surface. The chosen oil volume will be dependent on detectability by UV/Vis spectrophotometer or by weight, as well as the variability between SWA products and controls where no SWA product is added.
fields.b2_2: Salinity of Artificial Media: Initial tests will be conducted with artificial seawater (GP2 at 31 parts per thousand). After a successful protocol has been established with artificial seawater, additional work will include testing artificial freshwater to test the applicability of the protocol for determining SWA product effectiveness for an inland spill. The tables below define the makeup of the two aqueous matrices to be used during this research.
fields.b2_4: Substrate: Proposed oil attachment surfaces include ion exchange resins, glass microscope slides, stainless steel surfaces (coupons), ceramic tiles, glass sample vials, cellulose filter material and polypropylene media bottle caps. Other glass- or metal-based substrates might also be considered for the preliminary experiments. For the media bottle caps, the oil is added and weathered on the bottle cap then the bottle would contain artificial seawater followed by mixing (see Figure B1.1). The final decision on selection of the test surface will be made after preliminary testing has narrowed down the possible surfaces.
fields.b2_5: For every experiment, all serum bottles containing samples will be labeled with date of experiment, test descriptor, operator identity, SWA identifier, matrix type (seawater or freshwater), and replicate number (1-6). Each sample should also have on the label that the contents are in DCM solvent – the box containing the samples should also have a warning label on it - “Oil in DCM”.
fields.b2_6: Crude oils and SWA products do not require preservation, do not have holding times, and will be stored at room temperature.

A Shimadzu UV/Visible Spectrophotometer with standard silica 10 millimeter path length rectangular cells will also be for quantifying oil in DCM extracts. Absorbance measurements are recorded between 340- 400 nanometers (nm) where oil aromatic components absorb. Six calibration standards will be extracted and analyzed to create a six-point calibration curve. Once the calibration curve has been established, a mid-point check standard should be analyzed to confirm it meets specifications, then at minimum after every 10 samples and at the conclusion of the samples run (follow guidelines in PPM 13.4). For each oil, six concentrations of standards will be chosen to fall within the linear calibration range of the spectrophotometer. 

For each oil, six concentrations of standards will be chosen to fall within the linear calibration range of the spectrophotometer. Tables B2.1 and B2.2 contain spreadsheet examples of oil stock concentration determination and oil stock standard linearity and slope measurement.

fields.b1_1:
The models for this effort are of two types: material flow analyses and process models.  The material flow analysis of a plastic or anaerobic digestion system depends on how much of various products are generated, how much are consumed, how much are discarded, and how much are sent to recycling (plastics) or processing (anaerobic digestion).  Much of the data needed for model development is in the form of flow rates.  These flows are at a large scale for U.S. material flow analysis.  The data on flows might be found in various sources as described in Section A.7 or calculated based on relationships such as economics, where for instance, sales for a product are discovered along with a price per unit (perhaps through the U.S. Bureau of Economic Analysis).  Another source for cross-boundary flows could be U.S. Census data on dollar values of international transactions.  Thus, data on flows can be directly found or indirectly determined from other data, which similarly must be acquired.  

Modeling of processes for plastic recycling and anaerobic digestion require different types of data compared to the material flow analyses.  The flow rates needed for these models are relative to the process, e.g., feed flow rate, additive flow rate, production rate.  Process information such as required quantitative and qualitative data will be entered by the user and collected from various databases (e.g., journal articles, patents, National Emissions Inventory, Toxics Release Inventory).  Data will consist of design specifications, mass and energy flows, compositions, operating conditions, equipment configurations, utility specifications, reaction kinetics, physical and chemical properties, etc.  A desired result of process modeling is to estimate environmental releases.  Top-down database and bottom-up spreadsheet methods for estimating environmtnal releases from processes and various types of equipment have been developed in previous research and can be applied here (Cashman et al, 2016; Smith et al, 2017).  If water-based discharges are desired, it may be necessary to approximate them for the processes of interest or develop an appropriate model for process wastewater treatment.  

B.1.1 Functional Requirement - Ability to Create, Read, Update and Delete Data

The system will use multiple data files and databases for model development and will require the ability to read the data from the database, create additional records, update, and delete records.
The databases may be stored and maintained as Microsoft Excel® spreadsheets or tab delimited or comma-separated (csv) files.  Records can be added, modified, and deleted directly within the Excel® software.  The data tables can be saved from the Excel® spreadsheet as tab-delimited or comma separated text files.
fields.b1_2:
The two types of calculations needed for this research involve material flow analysis and process simulation.  Material flow analysis is a flow calculation, following flows of materials through the system.  Such calculations only require conservation of mass and therefore are simple to perform.  

Process simulation calculations may be needed.  If so, they can be done using shortcut methodologies or a standard simulation program such as CHEMCAD®.  The shortcut methods are simply performed on spreadsheets, with flows maintained using formulas to account for more difficult (but tractable) equations, for example, the recycle flows inside a process.  Simulation programs do these calculations as standard features within their programs.  The other types of calculations that a simulation program offers are for kinetic reactions and equilibrium-based separations.  These types of calculations have long been established within chemical engineering literature.  The benefits of a simulation program are equilibrium data held within the program and the ability to act as a sophisticated calculator.  Both of these features have been tested thoroughly by the simulation company (e.g., Chemstations) to maintain the accuracy of results developed with the simulation program

fields.b2_1:
The two types of mathematical representations developed for this research are material flow analyses and process models.  Material flow analyses are performed on types of products or a specific product.  For instance, a material flow analysis can be performed on plastics in general, or on a single plastic, such as polyethylene terephthalate.  Another example in this research is anaerobic digestion of food, agricultural, and other organic waste.  The material flow analyses completed for this research will focus on the United States as the boundary of interest.  Flows will need to be determined inside the U.S. and across its boundaries.  Flows are determined for different components inside the boundaries.  This will include how much of various products are generated, how much are consumed, how much are discarded, and how much are sent to recycling (plastics) or processing (anaerobic digestion).  Flows downstream from these recycling and processing steps may be of interest to follow the end-of-life products made and how they are used.  While not necessary to material flow analysis, a closely related type of calculation is a stock and flow model.  To approximate some flows for material flow analysis, it may be necessary in this effort to estimate a stock, for instance, how much plastic has accumulated in the system.  A fraction of the stock may be used to estimate a flow rate.  The standard balance equation for these systems is

Accumulation rate = Input rate – Output rate + Generation rate			(1)

where for steady state flows the accumulation rate is zero.  For stock and flow models, a stock can accumulate, so in that case a non-zero accumulation rate could exist.  Production and destruction processes will have a non-zero generation rate.  As an example, a steady state production process would have zero accumulation and input rates, so the output rate will equal the production (i.e., generation) rate.  Another aspect of material flow analysis is the time period of interest.  In this work the time period is expected to be one year (the most recent year, 2019, if possible), so that flows are determined on a yearly basis.  The results of material flow analyses can be reported in tables of flows or in diagrams.  Although other formats can be used, a common diagram for representing conserved flows is a Sankey Diagram (Sankey Diagram website, 2020), with a common example being the flows of different forms of energy through generation, transformation, and use.  Materials are represented similarly, although a material product also has an output flow after use, where it may be discarded, returned to the system as a feedstock, or transformed into an upcycled or downcycled product (i.e., something of greater or lesser value, respectively).
fields.b2_2: The models derived for processes such as plastic recycling and anaerobic digestion require different calculations compared to material flow analyses.  For processes the flows are maintained within a physical system (e.g., tanks and piping), except for materials that cross the system boundary.  Parts of a process can also be operated in a batch fashion, with material transported to batch locations inside the system boundary.  The time scale of processes is also relatively short, as complete processing may be completed in hours or days.  Normally, processes are assumed to operate at a steady state, so production rates for a year are spread over the total processing time for the year.  Depending on the sophistication of the process model, the attributes studied can include mass, energy, utility, waste, water discharge, and emission flows.  Mass and energy are conserved, while the other flows are of interest as results.  A generic model to calculate these flows based on parameters such as feedstock material, feedstock flow, equipment configuration, etc. will be developed.  To the extent possible, data will match technology types, with attention paid to process size, batch vs. continuous, reactions, separations, pollution controls, pollution treatment, and other details. Where appropriate, process models will be differentiated according to the technologies used.  Technology specific data will be documented with ranges, as available, to describe their variability and uncertainty, with variability indicative of inherent heterogeneity, and uncertainty expressing a lack of knowledge.  Specific or averaged versions of the results will be exported as results to generate a “unit process” for the USEEIO modeling effort.  A unit process is the smallest identifiable process with input-output information and a basis for calculation, such as 1 ton of product.  If necessary for product use, life cycle data quality indicators that are specific to life cycle assessment methodologies, will be determined (Edelen and Ingwersen, 2018).  To provide interesting analyses in publications the plastic and anaerobic models might be compared to other models for similar products or processes.
fields.b2_3: If necessary, statistical and related methods will be used to approximate parameters or flows for the modeling of material flow analyses and process models.  These methods are described in a recent QAPP, K-LRTD-0032566-QP-1-0, Application of Statistical Inferencing for Generic Exposure Scenario Modeling (QAPP, 2020).  Regression methods can be used for simple systems of features and outcome variables, and machine learning methods can be applied for larger varied datasets for prediction of unknown values.  The usefulness of such methods depends on the similarity of independent systems to the system of interest, where the system of interest has data gaps.  When the qualitative or quantitative similarity is visibly explainable (i.e., intuitive) the analysis is called read-across, which is another method for filling data gaps explained in the above QAPP.
fields.b3_2: A data quality evaluation revealing that quality indicators (e.g., the geography, technology, or time represented for a process) are not matches with U.S. boundaries, exact process setups, or year of interest will not necessarily lead to not using data.  Such data might be the best available.  Evaluations will have to be made to most nearly meet the desires of boundaries, process setup, time, and other circumstances of representativeness.
fields.b3_3: Once the criteria above are evaluated for secondary data, and a choice of what data to use is available, the order of use will be according to the following hierarchy.  Data from U.S. Federal and State databases will be prioritized, followed by U.S. Federal and State government publications.  It is believed that U.S. Federal and State databases and publications have had the most scrutiny and direct applicability to U.S. conditions.  The decision of whether to use international government databases and publications may be decided above if the data is a better fit for representativeness (process setup, year of interest, etc.).  It’s expected that international government databases and publications will be strongly peer-reviewed, and thus of high quality, although discrepancies with U.S. conditions may exist.  The tradeoff between data quality and representativeness will likely have to be made for many data sources.  Likewise, the hierarchy will follow with literature found in peer-reviewed and then non-peer-reviewed encyclopedias, books and journals, trade journals, followed by engineering judgment of experts, and lastly by engineering judgment of the principal investigators.  The rationale in applying this order of data sources is to use sources having the highest levels of scrutiny and applicability, which may finally be up to the principal investigator’s discretion.
fields.b3_4: When data sources are copied from an original source into spreadsheets, databases, or other calculators (e.g., chemical process simulators) the values will be double checked to verify that migration was done accurately.  Data will be checked to be between upper and lower limiting values for reasonableness to help prevent inconsistencies.  Mass balances (Equation 1) will be rechecked for errors, either in data or calculations.
fields.b4_1:
Testing of data will examine the data types and model results.  The most common data type will be floating point numbers.  Thus, a float (spreadsheet Number or Scientific format) versus string (spreadsheet Text format) data type check will be done, as will a test that money is represented in a Currency format.  Model results will be checked for reasonableness; especially the relative rates of flows will be examined.  Without known data and results to compare to, the models will have to be validated through engineering judgment.  If model results are available at different scales, i.e., regions of the U.S., then National results can be compared to them, while acknowledging that regional values are part of National values.  References in the literature may be useful for comparisons, although the accuracy of other models is not known.  Any model parameters that could strongly change (especially nonlinearly) the results will be tested through sensitivity analysis.  

Per standard policy, all products of this project will be externally reviewed.  Any journal articles have peer-review done as part of the publication process.  Other products will have separately developed peer-reviews completed.

fields.d1: Data packages will be prepared by the primary analyst and will include raw data from the instrument, spectra (if any), processed data and final results. This data package will be reviewed by a secondary analyst or QA Manager. During this review, at least 10% of the data will be checked for transcription and calculation errors. The QA/QC acceptance criteria and flagging will also be checked.
fields.d2: Data packages prepared by the primary analyst will be reviewed by a secondary analyst or QA Manager. During this review, at least 10% of the data will be checked for transcription and calculation errors. The QA/QC acceptance criteria and flagging will also be checked. the review will be documented by a review form, through notations in lab notebooks or through emails. Additional QA/QC review may be conducted upon request of the CESER QA Manager. The results generated from this study may be disseminated through presentations, posters, reports, journal articles or standard operating procedures. For each of these, the products may undergo additional peer-review according to established ORD procedures.
fields.d3:
The data generated under this research is considered exploratory, i.e., determining the number of microplastics in food-waste. As such, the results are expected to be reported as a value along with RSD from triplicate measurements. If an additional study is warranted (e.g., comparing microplastic concentrations among different sources, locations, seasons, etc.), the QAPP will be modified to include these additional research objectives.

Final Products:
1. Initial report prepared by the EPA staff with contractor support on the existing data/literature review of food waste de-packaging equipment available on the market in real-world settings. The report is to include observations on the success of equipment in limiting the number of micro-plastics entering food.
2. Final report prepared by the EPA staff with contractor support on food waste sampling and analysis.

fields.d1: Model verification will be completed using a number of techniques. The model generated total environmental emissions associated with full US output will be checked against national emission or resource use totals. The model generated total commodity output to meet US output demand will be checked against the reported US total commodity output. National emissions or resource use totals will come from the original data providers used to create the sources. Total US commodity output will be derived from the published Use table. Model validation tests will include import of independent data and comparison of these data against model generated totals.
fields.d2: Because methods for quantitative model uncertainty analysis for EEIO models have not been established, model uncertainty is primarily addressed using sensitivity analysis, gravity analysis, and model comparison methods. The implementation of these types of analyses performed will vary based on the possible model uses. The primary means of model evaluation will be though a standardized process for data quality scoring and data quality assessment. This process will be based on the LCA data quality assessment guidelines described in an EPA report (Edelen and Ingwersen, 2016) and illustrated in the USEEIO v1 documentation (Yang et al., 2017). When a USEEIO model is applied by the project team, the resulting data quality assessment scores will be used in the interpretation of the results. A secondary means of model evaluation will be through model comparison. With each build of a USEEIO model, one or more previous model versions will be selected for comparison. Results from each model will be compared using standardized comparison procedures. Reports of model comparisons will be maintained along with internal project files according to the approved Scientific Data Management plan (Ingwersen, 2015).
fields.d3: All new modeling techniques and methods for USEEIO models will be submitted for external peer-review. Model code and data files will be provided to reviewers, so they will have the means of checking model output against reported model results as well as reviewing the scientific validity of the described methods.

fields.d1: Data review will be documented by using the Data Review Form included here as Appendix C. This review will need to also document the use of QC checks throughout the data collection process. Data verification and validation will be conducted in accordance with the Pegasus QMP data review process which in turn, is based on the guidance provided in the EPA document entitled, Guidance on Environmental Data Verification and Validation, EPA QA/G-8.
fields.d2: Data qualification is an integral component of data reporting, review and validation. During data reporting and review, qualifiers are applied to ensure the laboratory has provided data of known quality. During data validation, qualifiers are applied to alert the data end user to quality problems that may impact the usability of the data. Data qualifiers may be assigned to particular sample results based on available information, including: laboratory QC summaries, unavoidable analytical interference, laboratory data summary information, etc. The data qualifiers and other data descriptors to be used in this project are below in Table D3.1 and D3.2.
fields.d3: The data will be evaluated to check if they conform to the QA objectives of the project. A statistical assessment for accuracy and precision will be performed. Data analyses will need to meet the requirements listed in Table B5.1 before formulation of the interim reports. The individual EPA Method or SOPs documenting an analysis will include a discussion of data verification, including ascertaining matrix effects and instrumental biases. Where failures are observed in the individual methods during analyst review, data will be marked as suspect and the WAL will be informed. Any necessary changes required will be documented in the laboratory notebook as well as documenting on the data review form (Appendix C).

fields.source_title: Feasibility Study on the Application of Fabricated Multipurpose Food Packaging Plastic (MFPP) Liner as Alternative Landfill Liner Material in Sustainable Landfill Infrastructure Model
fields.citation: Feasibility Study on the Application of Fabricated Multipurpose Food Packaging Plastic (MFPP) Liner as Alternative Landfill Liner Material in Sustainable Landfill Infrastructure Model. https://www.scientific.net/KEM.821.343.
fields.comments: Multipurpose Food Packaging Plastic (MFPP) is one of the largest residential and commercial solid waste all over the world. BWP is categorized under Non-Biodegradable Plastic Waste (N-BPW). Due to its inability to degrade, this abundance of N-BPW caused space decrement in landfill. Many methods have been proposed for recycling of N-BPW such as incorporating N-BPW into road construction and added material in concrete production. In the present study, the feasibility of using MFPP as landfill liner material is studied through a series of laboratory testing in terms of mechanical and chemical characteristics. The liner sample was prepared in terms of a fabricated layer (combination of 60 layers (Sample A) and 80 layers (Sample B) of a single plastic). The fabricated layers were prepared by applying hot-pressing technique to increase the strength of the surface attachment between each of the layers. The prepared fabricated MFPP liners were tested for Ultimate Tensile Strength Test (UTS), Scanning Electron Microscopy (SEM) and X-Ray Distraction (XRD). The tested samples were then compared with the Conventional Geomembranes (GMs). Obtained results indicated that proposed fabricated MFPP Liner had 70% similar characteristics to GMs. In addition, the fabricated MFPP Liners have an ability to sustain maximum loading higher than Conventional GMs. These desirable characteristics indicated that the fabricated MFPP Liners has potential to be used as landfill liner material.

fields.source_title: Microplastics, a food safety issue?
fields.keywords:
Microplastics
POPs
Toxicity
Nanoplastics
Risk assessment
fields.citation: Rainieri S., Barranco A. (2019)  Trends in Food Science and Technology,  84 , pp. 55-57.
fields.comments:
Review Description
The risk posed by microplastics for human and environment, has become a hot topic. The concern is focused not only on the effect of microplastics as such but also on additives and chemical contaminants absorbed by microplastics that may be released and affect negatively animals and environmental health. Despite several works have been written on this topic, a number of knowledge gaps still should be filled to enable a correct risk assessment of this important issue. For example, the relevance of microplastics for food safety has not yet been fully established and scientific results aimed at establishing a possible health risk for contaminants associated with microplastics are rather controversial. The risk assessment of microplastics in foodstuff is still at a very early stage and very few studies on the monitoring of microplastics in foodstuff and their effects on human health are available. Additionally, it is difficult to compare results from different studies as methodologies and study designs are not uniform. For this reason, it is not always possible to reach some definitive conclusion. This work sets out to complement the reviews and statements already existing, by updating the information and identifying if any of the knowledge gaps have been covered and if further ones have been detected with the final aim of properly assessing and managing this emerging risk.

fields.source_title: Effects of food presence on microplastic ingestion and egestion in Mytilus galloprovincialis
fields.keywords: Plastic particle, Mussel, Egestion rate, Mytilus gallo, provincialis marine pollution
fields.citation: xxx
fields.comments: Research on plastic pollution in marine environments has increased exponentially in the recent decades (Strungaru et al., 2019, Alimba and Faggio, 2019). In particular, small particles of manufactured or weathered plastic (microplastics (MPs), <5 mm), characterized by global abundance, have been studied extensively. MPs are widely distributed and have been monitored in polar regions (Lusher et al., 2015, Waller et al., 2017), tropical regions (Lima et al., 2014, Do Sul et al., 2014), the East (Ng and Obbard, 2006, Isobe et al., 2015), the West (Claessens et al., 2011, Collignon et al., 2012, Alomar et al., 2016, Bellas et al., 2016), coastal areas (de Lucia et al., 2014, Stolte et al., 2015), open seas (Reisser et al., 2014, Romeo et al., 2015), sea surfaces (Song et al., 2014, Song et al., 2015), and the deep sea (Van Cauwenberghe et al., 2013, Taylor et al., 2016).
